The International Arctic Science Committee (IASC) is a non-governmental, international scientific organization. IASC?s mission is to encourage and facilitate cooperation in all aspects of Arctic research, in all countries engaged in Arctic research, and in all areas of the Arctic region. IASC promotes and supports leading-edge interdisciplinary research in order to foster a greater scientific understanding of the Arctic region and its role in the Earth system.



To achieve this mission, IASC:

- Initiates, coordinates, and promotes scientific activities at a circumarctic or international level;

- Provides mechanisms and instruments to support science development;

- Provides objective and independent scientific advice on issues of science in the Arctic and communicates scientific information to the public;

- Seeks to ensure that scientific data and information from the Arctic are safeguarded, freely exchangeable and accessible;

- Promotes international access to all geographic areas and the sharing of knowledge, logistics, and other resources;

- Provides for the freedom and ethical conduct of science;

- Promotes and involves the next generation of scientists working in the Arctic; and

- Promotes polar cooperation through interaction with relevant science organizations.



The Arctic is critical to understanding the Earth system, as well as a focal point for climate change. It is intimately connected to the global system via ocean, land, and air masses, as well as the people that inhabit and/or are connected economically to the Arctic region. This is an unprecedented time in terms of rapid changes occurring in the Arctic, and our abilities to understand, predict, and respond to those changes are of US and international strategic interest. No single country is able to support the level of research necessary to keep pace with the changing Arctic, and therefore organizations like IASC represent vital platforms for discussing scientific issues and promoting international, interdisciplinary, and in some cases large-scale projects in the region. The impacts from melting sea ice on biogeochemical cycles, thawing permafrost and resulting change to the carbon cycle, biodiversity and northward species migration and ecosystem reorganization, and associated human interactions and response to environmental and social changes in rapidly transforming social-economic conditions all link the Arctic to the global system and represent issues so important and so large that no one country can adequately address them in isolation. The US delegates to IASC maintain US leadership and partnerships in the international community, as well as planning and coordinating roles for research collaborations in the international arena.



The US delegates to IASC maintain the strength and leadership the US has built over recent decades in international Arctic science.  The US has taken a strong advocacy position in promoting international collaboration and cooperation in matters of Arctic observations, analyses, and synthesis.  The US is clearly a leader in initiating and executing scientific expeditions, conducting large-scale programs and developing new methods of measurements and analyses, but the problem of understanding the Arctic system is of far too great a magnitude for the US to attack without international partners.  The Arctic is an extremely difficult and dangerous place to work, so it is critically important to share and utilize the results of efforts from all nations.  IASC offers a respected mechanism to formulate international collaborative programs and to develop protocols on sharing data and understanding.  IASC presents the formal structure to create new opportunities for international cooperation, support early career scientists and Indigenous scholars.  IASC and the participating partners enable us to extract more value from the research conducted by our scientists, while allowing all scientists and nations to benefit from the work of others.

The collaborative research programs envisioned, created and promoted under the auspices of the IASC banner have enabled projects of great magnitude and implications due to the collective engagement of many nations.  MOSAiC is a terrific recent example (among dozens) of a collaborative program created within IASC, but now with international sponsorship that will contribute substantially to our understanding of ice-ocean-atmosphere interactions.  IASC strives and succeeds in creating collaborative Arctic research endeavors for the benefit of the US and all nations.

IASC initiates, promotes and supports dozens of coordinating workshops each year.  Our culminating event is the annual Arctic Science Summit Week (ASSW) that attracts hundreds of participants and dozens of organizations to meet in one place at one time to foster partnerships and enhance sharing of Arctic data, understanding, resources and facilities.  A more complete description of the dozens of events and outcomes is provided in our annual bulletin: https://iasc.info/communications/bulletin

